Pick different stocks

tickers_today <- c("CXW", "F", "GM", "JCP", "KR", "WDC", "NKE","T", "WDAY", "WFC", "WMT")

Give the date range

start <- today() - years(5)
end <- today()

Stock price information for chosen stocks

Interact <- tq_get(tickers_today, get = 'stock.prices', from = start, to = end)
## Warning: x = 'JCP', get = 'stock.prices': Error in getSymbols.yahoo(Symbols = "JCP", env = <environment>, verbose = FALSE, : Unable to import "JCP".
## argument "conn" is missing, with no default
##  Removing JCP.

Plot of stock prices for chosen stocks

Interact_plot <- Interact %>%
  select(symbol, date, adjusted) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = symbol, values_from = adjusted) %>%
  tk_xts(date_var = date) 
## Warning: Non-numeric columns being dropped: date
dygraph(Interact_plot) %>%
  dyRangeSelector()

Monthly returns for chosen stocks

My_monthlyReturns <- Interact %>%
  group_by(symbol) %>%
  tq_transmute(adjusted, mutate_fun = monthlyReturn) %>%
  select(symbol, date, monthly.returns) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = symbol, values_from = monthly.returns) %>%
  tk_xts(date_var = date)
## Warning: Non-numeric columns being dropped: date
dygraph(My_monthlyReturns) %>%
  dyOptions(colors = RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(3, "Set2")) %>%
  dyRangeSelector()

Candlestick plot of stock volumes

Interact %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = volume)) +
  geom_candlestick(aes(open = open, high = high, low = low, close = close)) +
  labs( y = "Volume",
        x = "") + 
  coord_x_date(xlim = c(start, end)) +
  facet_wrap(~ symbol, scale = "free_y") + 
  theme_tq()

I chose to make a dygraph for the stock prices so that I could easily compare the different prices of the different stocks. I also added in the dyRangeSelector so that it could look closer at specific dates, such as highs and lows of the stock prices. For example, I was able to look at how the stock prices dropped in March becasue that is whenever COVID started to become a larger issue. I also decided to look into the monthly returns. It was interesting to see that they were so dispersed a year ago, but they are more bunched and similar as the year goes on. Also, it shows that during COVID, people were losing money in these stocks. Finally, I made a candlestick plot to look at the volumes of the stock prices for the stocks. From this graph I was able to note that Ford, General Motors, Kroger, Nike, Workday, and Walmart had upward trends in volume, so these are probably better ones to invest in.
